Philip Gordon has been appointed as the Special Assistant to the President and White House Coordinator for the Middle East, North Africa, and the Gulf Region. He will start his duties on March 11. National Security Advisor Tom Donilon praised Gordon's work with European allies and partners, particularly in addressing issues in Libya, Syria, and Iran. Gordon has previously served as the Assistant Secretary of State for European and Eurasian Affairs and has worked in various foreign policy roles, including as a senior advisor to President Barack Obama's 2008 campaign. He holds a Ph.D. and M.A. in international relations from Johns Hopkins University School of Advanced International Studies (SAIS) and a B.A. from Ohio University.